04289nam a22006255i 9781501737923DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20191997nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017379237 a10.7591/97815017379232doi  a(DE-B1597)534488  a(OCoLC)1143821999  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0320002bisacsh1 aStockdale, Melissa Kirschke, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPaul Miliukov and the Quest for a Liberal Russia 1880-1918 /cMelissa Kirschke Stockdale. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (408 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tNote on Transliteration, Titles, and Dates -- tCHAPTER ONE. Youth and Student Years -- tCHAPTER TWO. Political Awakening -- tCHAPTER THREE. Miliukov’s Historical Thought -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Scholarship and Opposition -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Russian Liberalism -- tCHAPTER SIX. The Revolution of 1905 -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. The Search for Unity, 1907-1914 -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. The War Years -- tCHAPTER NINE. Miliukov Displaced -- tConclusion -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPaul N. Miliukov was one of the most formidable intellectual and political forces of Russia's late imperial period. A historian of international reputation, Miliukov eventually became the principal theoretician and leader of Russian liberalism. He helped found the country's first liberal political party, led the party's faction in the Duma, and edited an influential liberal daily. In 1917, Miliukov took the lead in organizing the first Provisional Government. Working tirelessly for a liberal order committed to social reform as well as political liberties and the rule of law, Miliukov also strove to reconcile liberalism and nationalism, championing the rights of national minorities while trying to promote the cohesion of the increasingly fragile empire.Melissa Kirschke Stockdale's biography of Miliukov's life in Russia is the most comprehensive available in any language. Drawing on his enormous published oeuvre and the five thousand folders of his personal archives in Moscow, many never before available to Western scholars, she examines Miliukov's contributions to Russian historiography, liberal thought, and nationality relations, teases out the connections between his historical writing and his political practice, and assesses his career in a European as well as a Russian context. In so doing, she illuminates the dilemmas involved in constructing a workable liberalism in an illiberal climate, dilemmas with a startling contemporary relevance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173792340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501737923423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501737923/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK